The article announces two nominations and appointments. William Charles McIntosh of Michigan has been nominated to be an Assistant Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency for International and Tribal Affairs. McIntosh has a 39-year career in environmental protection, having worked as a regulator and as a regulated manufacturer. He has experience in environmental permitting and compliance activities in Michigan and was involved in environmental statutory and regulatory reform as Governor Engler's Environmental and Natural Resources Advisor. McIntosh also worked for Ford Motor Company, managing environmental permitting, compliance, and improvements at Ford manufacturing facilities.

Kenneth S. George of Texas has been nominated to be the Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States of America to the Oriental Republic of Uruguay. George previously served as Assistant Secretary and Director General of the U.S. & Foreign Commercial Service in the Department of Commerce. He has also served as a State Representative in the Texas House of Representatives and has held various positions on city, State, and professional boards and commissions in Texas. Since 2009, George has been the owner and manager of Blue Harbor Plantation and Blue Harbor Tropical Arboretum in Roatan, Honduras. He holds a B.A. from Washington and Lee University and an M.B.A. from the University of Texas at Austin.